    • [ - ] SteveHyland - member since 03-Nov-12

      @neumi17- The quality players came before the (international) tv money did. Regardless, Wenger would actually prefer a team full of Englishmen. Why? Firstly, because the majority would in all likelihood come from the academy therefore cost no money other than wages. Secondly, they'd all know the language so nothing would be lost in translation. Thirdly, they'd know what the league is all about and none of it's characteristics (physicality primarily) would come as a shock. Lastly, no adapting period would be needed for players to settle into life in a new country. We'll in all likelihood sign a top striker before the window closes for ca. £45m. It'd be so much easier (and obviously cheaper) to promote a player from the academy who is ready. The fact is English players aren't in prem teams primarily because they aren't good enough. We have a few out on loan who look promising, ditto for Chelsea. I'm in favour of an 8-3 rule as long as the 3 are English not British or 'home-grown'.

      1 day ago

    • [ - ] SteveHyland - member since 03-Nov-12

      @neumi17- part 2: but lorded as the Dutch way of youth football/development is, they've never won a world cup and are perennial underachievers. Spain have been great but possession football in it's purest form is dead- even Barcelona have needed to adapt because teams learned how to defend against them. Germany did well at the world cup but it's not inconceivable that another team playing a different style of football wins Euro '16 in which case the German model will be obsolete. In the late 90's and early 00's it was the French way. I agree teaching raw skills to children is important, the younger the better since it's easier to learn and internalise but unless you come up with a style which is successful for that era or one which is always going to give you a chance then no amount of skill training will automatically equal success. It also helps that in Germany, Spain, Italy, Brazil and Argentina football is practically the only big professional team sport.

    • [ - ] SteveHyland - member since 03-Nov-12

      @neumi17- part 1: I don't disagree, I meant in regards to English players NOW. Putting them in prem teams would only diminish the team's overall ability. I can tell you for definite that the 'skills' you refer to are most definitely being taught at the academies of Arsenal, Man City, Chelsea, Southampton and Man Utd to name a few. English clubs were a bit behind in the technical aspect but since the majority Wenger's successful pre-Emirates era, many of the top clubs approach coaching the way he does, managers of the top clubs are stressing the passing and movement over pure speed and nutrition is viewed as important- even in youngsters as young as 6. It will take time for the hard work to come to fruition, maybe a generation...
